{"detail":{"ID":384,"post_author":"1","post_date":"2017-03-28 03:49:00","post_date_gmt":"2017-03-28 03:49:00","post_content":"Tripods face each other across the floor suggesting an invisible geometry of space. They split the room into behind-between-beyond (or before-during-after). Seen metaphorically, they can be the scale models for a city of the future, a city of towers five hundred meters tall, one half of the space given to urban parks, a human density twice that of Hong Kong with the air full of blue triangular light. Seen objectively, they are six-meter-tall, one-and-a-half-millimeter-thick, steel lattice tripods, their surface formed by strips of three centimeters placed every twelve centimeters. The tripods have a footprint of thirty-four centimeters by \u202fthirty-four centimeters, two arms or legs rising at thirty degrees from the vertical, one to four meters seventy centimeters and the other to three meters twenty centimeters.","post_title":"<p>Beijing Tripod, Beijing, CN 2008<\/p>","post_excerpt":"","post_status":"publish","comment_status":"closed","ping_status":"closed","post_password":"","post_name":"beijing-tripod-cn-2008","to_ping":"","pinged":"","post_modified":"2017-05-10 16:15:15","post_modified_gmt":"2017-05-10 16:15:15","post_content_filtered":"","post_parent":0,"guid":"http:\/\/obra.neptuno.digital\/?post_type=projects&#038;p=384","menu_order":0,"post_type":"projects","post_mime_type":"","comment_count":"0","filter":"raw","ancestors":[],"page_template":"","post_category":[],"tags_input":[],"extended":{"year":"","images":[{"image":{"width":1500,"height":926,"file":"2017\/03\/OBRA_BEIJING_TRIPOD_02.jpg","sizes":{"thumbnail":{"file":"OBRA_BEIJING_TRIPOD_02-760x460.jpg","width":760,"height":460,"mime-type":"image\/jpeg"},"medium":{"file":"OBRA_BEIJING_TRIPOD_02-300x185.jpg","width":300,"height":185,"mime-type":"image\/jpeg"},"medium_large":{"file":"OBRA_BEIJING_TRIPOD_02-768x474.jpg","width":768,"height":474,"mime-type":"image\/jpeg"},"large":{"f